<TITLE> Bollywood, Hollywood to jointly fight piracy </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MUMBAI, Mar 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Leading Bollywood film producers joined hands with the Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA) on Thursday to curb piracy in one of the world's biggest film markets. UTV Motion Pictures, Reliance Big Entertainment and YashRaj Films are among those putting their financial muscle behind the MPAA's efforts, especially on camcorder piracy. The initiative, announced on the closing day of the FICCI Frames industry conference in Mumbai, will also target online piracy and counterfeit DVDs. "As many as 700 million discs are being sold and it is generating as much as 1,500 crore (15 billion) rupees, all in illegal business," Harish Dayani, CEO of Moser Baer Entertainment, said at a press conference. "If we don't halt this, then brand Bollywood will suffer." MPAA chairman Dan Glickman said if Hollywood and Bollywood wanted to work together on films like "My Name is Khan" and "Slumdog Millionaire", they had to first come together to fight piracy. Piracy is rampant in Bollywood and a 2008 report by Ernst & Young found the Indian film industry lost $959 million and 571,896 jobs to the bootleg sector. "We are a two-billion dollar industry and if we are losing close to a billion dollars a year due to piracy then it is very serious and it is time we came together to fight it," said Siddharth Roy Kapur, CEO of UTV Motion Pictures. In September, two executives working in film distribution companies were arrested for their alleged involvement in aiding and abetting pir
